metropolitan-scale inequality. While many accounts of education in urban and metropolitan contexts describe schools as the victims of forces beyond their control, Erickson shows the many ways that schools have been intertwined with these forces and have in fact—via land-use decisions, curricula, and other tools—helped sustain inequality. Taking Nashville as her focus, Erickson uncovers the hidden policy choices that have until now been missing from popular and legal narratives of inequality. In her account, inequality emerges not only from individual racism and white communities’ resistance to desegregation, but as the result of long-standing linkages between schooling, property markets, labor markets, and the pursuit of economic growth. By making visible the full scope of the forces invested in and reinforcing inequality, Erickson reveals the complex history of, and broad culpability for, ongoing struggles in our schools.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBusing for school integrationzTennesseezNashvillexHistoryy20th century. 0aEducational equalizationzTennesseezNashvillexHistoryy20th century. 0aSchool integrationzTennesseezNashvillexHistoryy20th century. 0aSegregation in educationzTennesseezNashvillexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  asegregation, desegregation, limits, limitations, educational, education, school, academic, scholarly, classroom, teacher, student, race, racism, politics, political, legal, law, litigation, unequal, inequality, equality, equal, rights, social studies, justice, policy, urban, metropolitan, white, black, community, tennessee, nashville, south, southern states, usa, america, american, history, historical, busing, tokenism, curriculum, true story.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 201